'''Henry Lawrence Blamires''' (17 April 1871 &ndash; 18 August 1965) was a [[New Zealand]] [[first-class cricket]]er and [[clergyman]].

==Personal life and clerical career==
One of five brothers who became clergymen, Henry Blamires was born in [[Bendigo]], [[Australia]], and educated at [[Wesley College (Victoria)|Wesley College]] in [[Melbourne]], which was then a [[Methodist]] school for boys. He was ordained in 1900<ref>[http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-Cyc02Cycl-t1-body1-d3-d3-d20.html The Cyclopedia of New Zealand 1902, Hamilton]</ref> and married Jane Collier, a teacher of the blind, the same year. They had three children.<ref>[http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/biographies/2c26/collier-jane-annie Penelope Hansen, "Collier, Jane Annie", from the Dictionary of New Zealand Biography]</ref>

He served as a [[chaplain]] with the New Zealand forces in [[World War I]].<ref>[http://muse.aucklandmuseum.com/databases/general/Cenotaph/34894.detail?Ordinal=1&c_surname_search=blamires Cenotaph, Henry Lawrence Blamires]</ref>

==Cricket career==
Blamires played three first-class matches for [[Hawke's Bay cricket team|Hawke's Bay]]. In his first match, aged 40, against [[Wellington cricket team|Wellington]], he made 55 not out in the second innings. His brother [[Ernest Blamires|Ernest]] made his first-class debut in the same match, playing for Wellington.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/8/8606.html Wellington v Hawke's Bay 1911-12]</ref> In his next match the next season, also against Wellington, he made 37 in the first innings before being bowled by [[Clarrie Grimmett]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/9/9214.html Hawke's Bay v Wellington 1912-13]</ref> Two weeks later he captained Hawke's Bay against the touring [[Australia cricket team|Australians]], but was dismissed cheaply twice by [[Arthur Mailey]]. It was Blamires's last first-class match.

He continued to play cricket for many years. He played [[Hawke Cup]] matches in the 1920s for Wanganui, Nelson and Wairarapa,<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/21/21477/Miscellaneous_Matches.html Miscellaneous matches played by Henry Blamires]</ref> for whom in his last match at the age of 57 he top-scored with 56.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/123/123450.html Manawatu v Wairarapa 1928-29]</ref>

